SIMPLE: irrational
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: irrational
<hw>ir*ra"tion*al</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧r*r⟦acr⟧sh"⟦ucr⟧n*⟦ait⟧l)</pr>,
<pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>irrationalis</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>irrationnel</ets>. See <er>In-</er> not, and
<er>Rational</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Not rational; void of reason or understanding;
<as>as, brutes are <ex>irrational</ex> animals</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Not according to reason; having no rational basis;
clearly contrary to reason; easily disproved by reasoning; absurd; -- of
assertions and beliefs.</def> <specif>Hence, of actions:</specif>
<def>foolish; unreasonable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>It seemed utterly <qex>irrational</qex> any longer to maintain
it.</q> <rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>Not capable of being exactly
expressed by an integral number, nor by a ratio of integral numbers;
surd; -- said especially of roots. See <er>Surd</er>.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Absurd; foolish; preposterous; unreasonable;
senseless. See <er>Absurd</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>irrationality</ent>⟦br⟧
